Thanks for watching this video. I'm glad you're here. If you feel like this earns your subscription please click here: http://bit.ly/Subscribe2SED


How this happened: I messaged Tory "If you ever find yourself with an open lunch I'll buy. No cameras, just rocket geek chat."
A few months later he changed a flight one day so we could grab lunch, but he also carved out a couple of hours before lunch to give me a personal tour.
He's as cool off camera as he is on camera. He allowed me to ask any technical question I had, and I never even got close to the limits of his understanding of rockets. His technical prowess is something I aspire to. We made a video on the second channel where I interview him about more specific things about rockets, as well as how he feels about competitors.
2nd Channel Interview with Tory about rocket engines, competitors, and business philosophy: https://youtu.be/DQaPOIQLEUo

snippet.textDisplay:
I waited a few days to make sure I had an hour to commit to this video, but it feels like it flew by. I'm amazed at how much Tory knows. Clearly this video doesn't even scratch the surface of what's going on in that facility, but it's truly fascinating and I'd watch several more hours.

What strikes me with this is how no "regular" YouTuber could EVER have gotten this access or made it a meaningful use of such a busy CEO's time. Destin has the education, experience, and passion to ask intelligent, appropriate questions and engage in meaningful conversation while simultaneously bubbling with the joy of a child in a rocket factory. And even though some of the things discussed go far over my head, it was still enjoyable the entire time. Awesome job!

snippet.textDisplay: Destin, great video, thanks for the tour - outstanding!  Just want to say that you should try to find a copy of "Big Bets", the story of Southern Company's beginning if you would like to know more about why all that stuff is in that triangle around the Tennessee River. It started with hydro power for the people of Alabama, and to provide hydro power for a fertilizer plant for the farmers, then that all changed into using the fertilizer chemicals for weapons and the war, which then lead to missiles and nuclear research and rockets. Interesting history to say the least.
